meta {
  name: Tempo — fetch the trace and corroborate against Langfuse
  type: http
  seq: 3
}

get {
  url: {{tempoUrl}}/api/traces/{{traceId}}
  body: none
  auth: none
}

headers {
  Accept: application/json
}

script:post-response {
  if (res.getStatus() === 200) {
    const body = res.getBody();
    const names = [];
    for (const b of (body.batches || [])) {
      for (const ss of (b.scopeSpans || [])) {
        for (const s of (ss.spans || [])) names.push(s.name);
      }
    }
    names.sort();
    bru.setEnvVar("tempoSpanCount", String(names.length));
    bru.setEnvVar("tempoSpanNames", JSON.stringify(names));
    console.log("tempo spans:", names.length, names);
  }
}

tests {
  test("returns 200 — the trace reached Tempo", function() {
    // Tempo's API takes no auth (verified 2026-07-20). A 404 here with a
    // 200 from Langfuse is itself a finding: the OTel pipeline dropped a
    // trace the Langfuse SDK kept.
    expect(res.getStatus()).to.equal(200);
  });
  test("trace has at least one span", function() {
    expect(Number(bru.getEnvVar("tempoSpanCount"))).to.be.above(0);
  });

  test("CORROBORATION — every Langfuse observation is present in Tempo", function() {
    // The invariant is CONTAINMENT, not equality — corrected 2026-07-20
    // after a live run showed langfuse=5 tempo=17 on the same trace.
    // The two stores have different instrumentation scopes: Tempo receives
    // every OTel span (ASGI, DB, Redis, HTTP client — SELECT, SETEX,
    // connect, http send), while Langfuse receives only what the Langfuse
    // SDK observes. Tempo is therefore a superset by construction.
    //
    // A Langfuse observation with NO matching Tempo span is the real
    // anomaly: it means the OTel pipeline dropped a span the Langfuse SDK
    // kept. That is what this asserts.
    const lf = JSON.parse(bru.getEnvVar("langfuseObsNames") || "[]");
    const tp = JSON.parse(bru.getEnvVar("tempoSpanNames") || "[]");
    console.log(`langfuse=${lf.length} tempo=${tp.length}`);
    const missing = lf.filter(n => !tp.includes(n));
    if (missing.length) console.log("MISSING from Tempo:", missing);
    expect(missing).to.deep.equal([]);
  });
  test("Tempo's surplus spans are infrastructure, not lost application spans", function() {
    // Report the delta rather than hide it. This is descriptive, not a
    // pass/fail gate on an exact list — the auto-instrumented span set
    // changes with library versions and must not become a brittle pin.
    const lf = JSON.parse(bru.getEnvVar("langfuseObsNames") || "[]");
    const tp = JSON.parse(bru.getEnvVar("tempoSpanNames") || "[]");
    const surplus = tp.filter(n => !lf.includes(n));
    console.log(`tempo-only spans (${surplus.length}):`, [...new Set(surplus)].sort());
    expect(tp.length).to.be.at.least(lf.length);
  });
}

docs {
  **Step 3 of the evidence chain — the Tempo leg, and the comparison.**

  Fetches the same `{{traceId}}` from Tempo, counts spans across
  `batches[].scopeSpans[].spans[]`, and corroborates against the Langfuse
  figures captured in `01`. The comparison lives here because this
  request runs last and therefore holds both sides.

  **The invariant is containment, not equality** — corrected 2026-07-20
  by a live run. On a real request trace the two stores disagreed 5 vs
  17, and that disagreement was correct: Tempo receives every OTel span
  (ASGI `http send`/`http receive`, DB `SELECT`/`INSERT`, Redis `SETEX`,
  HTTP-client `GET`/`PUT`, `connect`), while Langfuse receives only what
  the Langfuse SDK observes. Tempo is a superset by construction.

  An earlier check passed 2 == 2 on a bootstrap trace whose only spans
  were DI/DB ones both stores happened to capture. That was a degenerate
  case masquerading as agreement — a direct instance of the noise hazard
  in this collection's other docs: validating a mechanism against
  infrastructure traces will teach you the wrong invariant.

  **What this proves, and what it does not.**

  Containment defeats one direction of *persistence-loss*: a Langfuse
  observation with no matching Tempo span means the OTel pipeline dropped
  something the SDK kept, and this fails. It does NOT defeat
  *emission-loss* — the same process feeds both stores, so a span never
  emitted is absent from both and they agree on a number that is wrong.
  Nor does it detect a Tempo-only span going missing, since surplus is
  expected. Say all of this plainly; it is the honest boundary of the
  technique.

  **The missing third leg — a real gap, recorded here.** The intended
  design corroborates THREE stores: Postgres `tool_calls`, Langfuse
  observations, Tempo spans. But as of 2026-07-20 the `tool_calls` table
  is exposed through no API endpoint — `_row_to_dict` in
  `routes/audit.py` returns no tool-call data, and there is no
  `/tool-calls` route in the OpenAPI document. So the Postgres leg
  cannot be reached through the front door, and this request corroborates
  two stores, not three.

  That gap bears directly on the "zero versus missing" question: an
  auditor holding a scoped JWT cannot today ask the system of record how
  many tool calls a given interaction made. Closing it means an additive,
  scope-gated read surface over `tool_calls`. Until then, this pair of
  requests is the strongest corroboration available through the API, and
  the shortfall belongs in any write-up rather than in a footnote.

  **Retention caveat:** Tempo's retention window bounds how long
  corroboration stays possible. A trace that has aged out returns 404
  here while Langfuse may still hold it — expected divergence, not a
  fault, but distinguish it from a genuine drop before reporting.
}
